Parliament, and in particular of Select Committees, in the final year before that election.  The main effect on select committees, in my opinion, is that knowledge of the date of the Election should allow for better planning, and encourage Member engagement, in the latter part of the Parliament.  A fixed date will not remove the risk that the focus of select committee members shifts away from committee work towards constituency and party matters as the Election nears, but it should mean that there is a longer period before this occurs.  In this respect, it should have a positive impact on select committee effectiveness.</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 28.25pt 10pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">13 January 2014 </span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>